\section*{Discussion}
\subsection*{Species responses to treatments}
Our results show how the growth response to different season length changed across different species. Photosynthates (products of photosynthesis) can be alocated to growth (biomass production), defense or storage. If the supply exceeds demand in an given season, trees store these compounds as non-structural carbohydrate (NSC), which they can use in a subsequent season \citep{chapin_ecology_1990,hessl_carbon_2026}. Populus reacting during the treatment year, but did not display a carry-over effect in 2025, in accordance with its non-determinate growth strategy (i.e. number of leaves is non pre-determined during the previous season). This strategy usually allows these species to be more flexible than their determinate counterpart \cite{baumgarten_invest_2025}---utilizing all carbon sources for growth seasonally, thus removing the capability of carry-over strategies. In contrast with Betula, sharing similar growth strategies, this species did not react to the treatments in 2024, but carried over a treatment effect in 2025. Moreover, the positive effect in 2025 of the warm spring treatments indicates that Betula may utilize the earlier start of season to increase its overall photosynthesis, allocating some of this excess of carbon supply to increase its growth in 2025. However, we may miss a mechanistic response of Betula to the treatments in 2024 that may underlie this unexpected behavior. \\

Quercus also reacted counterintuiativelly, excibiting a treatment effect on the current year growth, but not carried-over in the next year. Quercus being a determinate species, we did not expect it to react in the current year, instead exibiting treatment effects in the subsequent year. 

With Acer, Pinus and Prunus showing the same growth response across treatments indicates these  species may be little flexible, both in the short and long-term responses to growing season length.

Evergreen trees usually store less NSC because unlike deciduous trees---which require growing a new leaf cohort every spring---they keep most of their leaves and need fewer leaf growth investment \citep{hessl_carbon_2026,richardson_climate_2013}. Therefore, we explain the muted treatment effects of 2025 vs 2024 for Sequoiadendron by their seasonal strategy to primarily allocating their photosynthates directly to growth and defense and to a lesser extent, for long-term storage.

\subsection*{Model}
Our modelling approach has limitations. First, negative growth increments ($\Delta B$) in tree should be rare, but our normal likelihood allows for more of these values than it is realistically possible. Fitting the data using a log-normal likelihood would make these negative increments impossible, which is biologically more realistic.
Second, using a point estimate from the allometry model to fit the carry-over model, we used a "short-cut" that lacks statistical rigor. However, the posterior estimates for the allometry model, when fitting both models jointly, resulted in biomass independence from bounding box volumes (i.e. $\beta_2$ values approximating 0). In contrast, fitting the allometry model separately led to good posterior predictive checks showing the expected behavior of increasing biomass, with bounding box volume[?refer to figure]. This biomass independence of the full model, may be caused by issues with combining the posteriors of the allometry and carryover models, signified by the treatment effects and their corresponding likelihood error approximating zero. We deem these results from the full model to be improbable.

